likelihood of
prevailing on the merits.

11:45.104 --> 11:48.374 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's already reached that
conclusion that
we're likely to prevail once we
get to the

11:48.408 --> 11:50.243 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
merits before the judge.

11:50.276 --> 11:55.848 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Now, the Constitution
gives the
president authority to deal with
immigration,

11:55.882 --> 11:59.152 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to conduct foreign affairs and
address immigration.

11:59.185 --> 12:03.323 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Congress in the immigration law
gives the
president the power to restrict
or suspend

12:03.356 --> 12:06.859 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the entry of people he may deem
appropriate.

12:06.893 --> 12:09.128 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Why do you argue that this is
unconstitutional?

12:09.162 --> 12:11.631 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BOB FERGUSON: Well, it's pretty
straightforward.

12:11.664 --> 12:14.500 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Yes, the president has broad
authority.

12:14.534 --> 12:16.336 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We don't question that.

12:16.369 --> 12:19.105 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But what the federal government
is literally
arguing, and that your viewers
should be aware

12:19.138 --> 12:25.011 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of, is they're arguing that it's
unfettered,
that the court cannot look
behind any motivation

12:25.044 --> 12:27.680 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for that order or whether or not
it's constitutional.

12:27.714 --> 12:30.783 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that has never been the law
and simply
cannot be the law.

12:30.817 --> 12:32.485 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And we are a nation of laws.

12:32.518 --> 12:35.421 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And nobody can ignore our
Constitution.

12:35.455 --> 12:36.589 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
No one's above the law.

12:36.623 --> 12:38.391 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that includes the president
of the United
States.

12:38.424 --> 12:43.463 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: If this executive
order had just
called for the extreme vetting,
as President

12:43.496 --> 12:48.534 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Trump calls it, and not
specified countries,
not given preference to
Christians -- well,

12:48.568 --> 12:53.206 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it gives preference to religious
minorities
in these countries, which means
Christians

12:53.239 --> 12:58.878 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and other religions -- would
that have removed
the constitutional objections,
in your view?

12:58.911 --> 13:02.348 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BOB FERGUSON: Well, I'm often
asked about
different permutations that
might solve the

13:02.382 --> 13:04.117 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
significant problem the federal
government
has.

13:04.150 --> 13:06.719 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What I can say is, there is
pretty significant
vetting going on.

13:06.753 --> 13:10.923 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I just returned from Sea-Tac
Airport here
in Washington State, where I met
individuals

13:10.957 --> 13:14.727 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who had been denied entry to the
country as
a result of the president's
executive order,

13:14.761 --> 13:16.496 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
but are now back in.

13:16.529 --> 13:19.565 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And in one case, he had gone
through a through
a two-year process to get his
visa.

13:19.599 --> 13:23.503 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's now joining his wife, who's
a citizen
of this state, and his cousin,
who is a graduate

13:23.536 --> 13:26.205 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of Washington State University
and works at
Boeing.

13:26.239 --> 13:30.043 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
These are folks who would be
great additions
to our life in Washington State.

13:30.076 --> 13:31.911 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that's happening all across
the country
as well.

13:31.944 --> 13:36.149 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: So, we're learning
that the judge
has asked -- the appeals court
asked for oral

13:36.182 --> 13:37.517 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
arguments today.

13:37.550 --> 13:38.851 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Give us a preview.

13:38.885 --> 13:41.988 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What are you going to be saying
before this
three-judge panel?

13:42.021 --> 13:44.991 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BOB FERGUSON: So, you have news
that I just
am hearing for the first time.

13:45.024 --> 13:47.727 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, we're not surprised if
there's oral argument.

13:47.760 --> 13:50.797 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We anticipated that would be the
case for
an issue of this magnitude.

13:50.830 --> 13:55.101 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we will make the same case,
frankly, that
we made before Judge Robart,
that there can

13:55.134 --> 14:00.339 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
be no unfettered discretion for
a president,
that you have to look behind
what he's doing

14:00.373 --> 14:05.111 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
here, and that we find in this
case that it
violates various constitutional
provisions,

14:05.144 --> 14:08.214 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and also violates specific
statutory provisions
as well.

14:08.247 --> 14:09.482 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So we're confident we will
prevail.

14:09.515 --> 14:11.584 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: The president has
been tweeting
about this.

14:11.617 --> 14:18.057 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He said that this stay, this
temporary restraining
order, puts our country in such
peril, he

14:18.091 --> 14:19.859 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
says.

14:19.892 --> 14:23.663 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If something happens, blame him,
meaning the
judge, Judge Robart, and the
court system.

14:23.696 --> 14:25.131 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
How do you respond to that?

14:25.164 --> 14:28.167 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BOB FERGUSON: Well, look, a
couple things.

14:28.201 --> 14:33.072 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Number one, as a lawyer, his
comments about
the judge being a so-called
judge, for example,

14:33.106 --> 14:36.642 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
or statements like that are
deeply concerning
to anyone who cares about our
judiciary.

14:36.676 --> 14:41.581 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Number two, my wife and I, we
are raising
our twins, our young twins, to
be gracious

14:41.614 --> 14:43.282 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in victory or defeat.

14:43.316 --> 14:46.519 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And President Trump is obviously
having a
very difficult time handling the
defeat that

14:46.552 --> 14:48.988 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
he suffered before a federal
district court
judge.

14:49.021 --> 14:53.960 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: What about his
underlying argument,
though, that this is allowing,
this could

14:53.993 --> 14:57.096 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
allow a terrorist to come into
the country?

14:57.130 --> 15:01.033 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BOB FERGUSON: What did I would
encourage the
president to do is to draft an
executive order

15:01.067 --> 15:02.535 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
that's constitutional.

15:02.568 --> 15:03.536 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
That's his job.

15:03.569 --> 15:05.371 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's his responsibility.

15:05.404 --> 15:09.542 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
My job and my responsibility is
to make sure
that everybody, including the
president, plays

15:09.575 --> 15:11.611 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
by the rules and follows the
Constitution.

15:11.644 --> 15:15.081 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And in a courtroom, it is not
the loudest
voice that prevails.

15:15.114 --> 15:16.182 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's the Constitution.

15:16.215 --> 15:17.917 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that's why I think we're
prevailing right
now.

15:17.950 --> 15:21.087 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Attorney General Bob
Ferguson from
Seattle, thank you very much.

15:21.120 --> 15:22.922 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
BOB FERGUSON: Thank you.

15:22.955 --> 15:25.625 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JOHN YANG: And now for a
different take on
President Trump's executive
order, Republican

15:25.658 --> 15:29.529 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
